Data set creation

# Set the path to the downloaded data set
TurfGrassData <- read.csv("~/redatiX/Turf grass irrigation requirements/TurfGrassData.csv", row.names = NULL)

# Create IDs (Row names)
TurfGrassData <- TurfGrassData %>%
  mutate(combined_col = paste0(substr(Species, 1, 1), "_", Date, "_", Irrigation, "_", Sample))
rownames(TurfGrassData) <- TurfGrassData$combined_col
TurfGrassData <- data.frame(TurfGrassData[, -which(names(TurfGrassData) == "combined_col")])

# Ensure Total.precipitation is numeric
TurfGrassData$Total.precipitation <- as.numeric(TurfGrassData$Total.precipitation)

The rainfall received between the last grass cutting up to the day before the next cutting was categorised based on rainfall quantiles. [0.000 to 1.575 = Low, 1.576 to 3.700 = Moderate, 3.701 to 32.575 = High and 32.576 to 72.800mm = High]

# Determine the quantiles for the breaks for both columns
rainfall_quantiles <- quantile(TurfGrassData$Rainfall, probs = seq(0, 1, by = 0.25))
precipitation_quantiles <- quantile(TurfGrassData$Total.precipitation, probs = seq(0, 1, by = 0.25))

# Define the labels
labels <- c("Low", "Moderate", "High", "Very High")

# Convert to categorical data using quantiles and labels for both columns
TurfGrassData$Rainfall_cat <- cut(TurfGrassData$Rainfall, breaks = rainfall_quantiles, labels = labels, include.lowest = TRUE)
#View(TurfGrassData)
TurfGrassData$Precipitation_cat <- cut(TurfGrassData$Total.precipitation, breaks = precipitation_quantiles, labels = labels, include.lowest = TRUE)

Regression analysis

When two or more independent variables are highly correlated, it can lead to multicollinearity in your regression model. This can make it difficult to determine the individual effect of each variable on the dependent variable. However, whether to include both variables depends on the context and the degree of correlation. When dealing with multiple independent variables that could be correlated, its important to assess the correlations among all pairs of variables.

# Recalculate the correlation matrix:
cor_matrix <- cor(TurfGrassData_Kikuyu[, c(3, 5:12)])

# Function to calculate p-values
cor_test <- function(x) {
  FUN <- function(x, y) cor.test(x, y)[["p.value"]]
  z <- outer(
    colnames(x), colnames(x),
    Vectorize(function(i, j) FUN(x[, i], x[, j]))
  )
  dimnames(z) <- list(colnames(x), colnames(x))
  z
}

# Compute correlation matrix
cor_matrix <- cor(TurfGrassData_Kikuyu[, c(3, 5:12)], use = "complete.obs")

# Compute p-values matrix
p_matrix <- cor_test(TurfGrassData_Kikuyu[, c(3, 5:12)])

# Plot the correlation matrix with p-values
ggcorrplot(cor_matrix, method = "circle", lab = TRUE, p.mat = p_matrix, sig.level = 0.05)

NA
NA

Correlation coefficients as circles. Crossed out values for correlations that are not statistically significant (p-values > 0.05).

Interpreting the Correlation Matrix

Correlation Coefficients: The matrix shows the correlation coefficients for each pair of variables. High absolute values (e.g., |correlation| > 0.7) indicate strong correlations. Low absolute values indicate weak correlations.

Deciding Which Variables to Exclude

High Correlation: If two variables are highly correlated, consider excluding one of them. Domain Knowledge: Use your understanding of the subject matter to decide which variable is more relevant. Variance Inflation Factor (VIF): Calculate VIF to quantify the severity of multicollinearity.

Linear models that explain the variances of dependent variables

The Linear models are based on the correlation matrix results for Dry- and Wet.weight and Height as dependent variables. VIF measures how much the variance of a regression coefficient is inflated due to multicollinearity. A VIF value greater than 10 indicates high multicollinearity, suggesting the variable might be redundant. Partial R-squared values are useful for understanding the unique contribution of each predictor variable in the presence of other predictors. They help identify which variables have the most significant impact on the dependent variable when other variables are accounted for.

Although the homoscidasisity was confirmed by the Levines test, the data of all the irrigation groups were not normally distributed. Therefore, a non-parametric analysis of variance was performed to test the null hypothesis of no statistical differences between Dry.weight at different amounts of irrigation at the different rainfall quantiles.

Regression analysis

When two or more independent variables are highly correlated, it can lead to multicollinearity in your regression model. This can make it difficult to determine the individual effect of each variable on the dependent variable. However, whether to include both variables depends on the context and the degree of correlation. When dealing with multiple independent variables that could be correlated, its important to assess the correlations among all pairs of variables.

# Recalculate the correlation matrix:
cor_matrix <- cor(TurfGrassData_Cynodon[, c(3, 5:12)])

# Function to calculate p-values
cor_test <- function(x) {
  FUN <- function(x, y) cor.test(x, y)[["p.value"]]
  z <- outer(
    colnames(x), colnames(x),
    Vectorize(function(i, j) FUN(x[, i], x[, j]))
  )
  dimnames(z) <- list(colnames(x), colnames(x))
  z
}

# Compute correlation matrix
cor_matrix <- cor(TurfGrassData_Cynodon[, c(3, 5:12)], use = "complete.obs")

# Compute p-values matrix
p_matrix <- cor_test(TurfGrassData_Cynodon[, c(3, 5:12)])

# Plot the correlation matrix with p-values
ggcorrplot(cor_matrix, method = "circle", lab = TRUE, p.mat = p_matrix, sig.level = 0.05)

NA
NA

Correlation coefficients as circles. Crossed out values for correlations that are not statistically significant (p-values > 0.05).

Interpreting the Correlation Matrix

Correlation Coefficients: The matrix shows the correlation coefficients for each pair of variables. High absolute values (e.g., |correlation| > 0.7) indicate strong correlations. Low absolute values indicate weak correlations.

Deciding Which Variables to Exclude

High Correlation: If two variables are highly correlated, consider excluding one of them. Domain Knowledge: Use your understanding of the subject matter to decide which variable is more relevant. Variance Inflation Factor (VIF): Calculate VIF to quantify the severity of multicollinearity.

Linear models that explain the variances of dependent variables

The Linear models are based on the correlation matrix results for Dry- and Wet.weight and Height as dependent variables. VIF measures how much the variance of a regression coefficient is inflated due to multicollinearity. A VIF value greater than 10 indicates high multicollinearity, suggesting the variable might be redundant. Partial R-squared values are useful for understanding the unique contribution of each predictor variable in the presence of other predictors. They help identify which variables have the most significant impact on the dependent variable when other variables are accounted for.

Although the homoscidasisity was confirmed by the Levines test, the data of all the irrigation groups were not normally distributed. Therefore, a non-parametric analysis of variance was performed to test the null hypothesis of no statistical differences between Dry.weight at different amounts of irrigation at the different rainfall quantiles.

Non-parametric analysis of variance for Dry Weight

# Ensure that rainfall is a factor(categorical)
TurfGrassData_Cynodon$Rainfall_cat <- factor(TurfGrassData_Cynodon$Rainfall_cat, levels = c("Low","Moderate","High", "Very High"))

# Subset data for "Low" rainfall category
low_rainfall_Cynodon <- TurfGrassData_Cynodon %>% filter(Rainfall_cat == "Low")

# Subset data for "Moderate" rainfall category
moderate_rainfall_Cynodon <- TurfGrassData_Cynodon %>% filter(Rainfall_cat == "Moderate")

# Subset data for "High" rainfall category
high_rainfall_Cynodon <- TurfGrassData_Cynodon %>% filter(Rainfall_cat == "High")

# Subset data for "Very High" rainfall category
very_high_rainfall_Cynodon <- TurfGrassData_Cynodon %>% filter(Rainfall_cat == "Very High")

  dunnTest(Height ~ Irrigation, data = low_rainfall_Cynodon, method = "bonferroni")
